# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2024-baseball5-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] The **2022 Baseball5 World Cup** was the first edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Mexico City from 7 to 12 November 2022.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Cuba won the tournament, beating Japan in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Chinese Taipei finished third defeating Venezuela 2 matches to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 1There was no qualification event for WBSC Americas and WBSC Oceania.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Teams were selected by World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 2In October 2022, WBSC chose Hong Kong to replace Australia.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2023-baseball5-european-championship] The **2023 Baseball5 European Championship** was an international baseball5 tournament organized by the WBSC Europe.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2023-baseball5-european-championship] The championship was held from 7 to 11 November 2023, in the Lithuanian Sports Complex in Druskininkai, Lithuania and was contested between 13 national teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Hosts Lithuania won the tournament, beating France in the final 2 sets to 0, in a replay of the 2020 final (won by France).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Spain finished third defeating the Netherlands 2 sets to 1 in the bronze medal game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2023-baseball5-european-championship] Lithuania and France qualified for second time in a row to the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup to be held in the Central Harbourfront Event Space in Hong Kong.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-african-championship] The **2024 Baseball5 African Championship** was the second edition of the Baseball5 African Championship, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Africa.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-african-championship] The championship was held from 5 to 8 February 2024, in the Gimnodesportivo Vavá Duarte in Praia, Cape Verde and was contested between four national teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-african-championship] Tunisia won the tournament, defeating previous winners South Africa in the final game 2 sets to 0.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-african-championship] Hosts Cape Verde claimed the bronze medal, defeating Tanzania 2 sets to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-asia-cup] The **2024 Baseball5 Asia Cup** was the second edition of the Baseball5 Asia Cup, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Asia.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-asia-cup] The championship was held from 13 to 16 April 2024, in the Olympic Park in Seoul, South Korea and was contested between eight national teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-asia-cup] Japan won the tournament, defeating Chinese Taipei 2 sets to 1 in the final game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-asia-cup] China claimed the bronze medal, after defeating hosts South Korea 2 sets to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-asia-cup] Japan, Chinese Taipei and China qualify for the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup in Hong Kong.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship** was the first edition of the Baseball5 Pan American Championship, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Americas.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The championship was held from 27 to 30 June 2024, in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela and was contested between four national teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba went undefeated to win the tournament, finishing the opening round 6–0 and defeating Mexico in the championship game.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, claimed the bronze medal.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The three teams qualified for the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup in Hong Kong.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The **2024 Baseball5 World Cup** was the second edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Hong Kong from 7 to 12 October 2024.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The tournament was won by Cuba in their second straight Baseball5 World Cup title.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The Cuban team defeated Japan in the championship game, a replay of the 2022 final, 2 sets to 0 to finish the tournament undefeated with a 9–0 record.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] Cuban players Briandy Molina and Haila González received the Male MVP and Female MPV of the World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] France claimed the bronze after defeating Venezuela in the bronze medal game, 2 sets to 0.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The 2024 World Cup cost $12 million to host, with the Baseball Association of Hong Kong providing half of the funding.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The event has been given "M" Mark status (major sport event) by the Hong Kong government.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] The **Australia national Baseball5 team** represents Australia in international Baseball5 competitions.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia was scheduled to take part in the inaugural Baseball5 World Cup held in Mexico City in November 2022, but the team did not participate and was replaced by Hong Kong less than one month before the beginning of the tournament.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia made its Baseball5 World Cup debut in 2024 in Hong Kong.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] Trials were held in Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland to determine the squad that would play in the World Cup.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia debuted with two defeats on the first day of the tournament against Mexico and Japan.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/australia-national-baseball5-team] The team finished last in Group B in the Opening Round, losing their remaining games against China, Tunisia and France.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto was founded in 1552 by Juan de Villegas, as a headquarters and to have better control of the territory believed to be rich in gold.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Its original name was **Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto** and then it was shortened to just Barquisimeto.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] This city changed locations four times between 1552 and 1563.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The original settlement was near the Buría River, but moved in 1556 due to frequent floods suffered by inhabitants.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The second location was in the valley of the Turbio River, where the city stayed until Lope de Aguirre burned it down in 1561.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The city was rebuilt 102 km (63 mi), but in 1562 they inhabitants asked for permission to move to another site due to strong winds blowing in the place.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Finally, Barquisimeto was moved to the north plateau of the Turbio River in 1563.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] During the country's independence, Barquisimeto joined the liberation movement and its deputy José Ángel Álamo signed the Independence Act on July 5, 1811.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] In 1929, the city went through a modernization program carried out by General Juan Vicente Gomez.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] He fixed the streets and avenues and buildings were built, like the Jacinto Lara Headquarters, the Government Palace and the Ayacucho Park.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] According to the German adventurer Nikolaus Federmann, the Caquetío aborigines used to call it Variquicimeto, which translates as "ash-colored river", the name with which the natives distinguished the water stream near the city.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] This river was named "Turbio River" by the Spanish conquerors, a name that is still in use today.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Another possible name origin is due to a red dye called *bariquí*.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] When Juan de Villegas founded it, he named the city "Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto", but years later it became just "Barquisimeto", a word popularized by Oviedo y Baños in his book *History and Conquest of the Venezuelan Population*.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The city's modern Cathedral of Our Lady of Mount Carmel is the cathedral of the episcopal see of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Barquisimeto.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The Divina Pastora (Divine Shepherdess) is a statue of the Virgin Mary holding the infant Jesus, with a lamb at her side.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] It is considered to be one of the most important religious icons of Venezuela.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is the patron saint of the city of Barquisimeto and of the Venezuelan National Militia.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is celebrated in a procession on January 14 of each year, when a massive Marian procession occurs, considered to be one of the largest in the world, attracting thousands of pilgrims.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The statue is removed from its shrine and is carried on the main streets of Barquisimeto in a procession which starts at the Iglesia de la Divina Pastora in Santa Rosa until it reaches the Barquisimeto Cathedral.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] This procession is unlike other mass Marian celebrations in the world, where the image does not leave its temple.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] This procession occurs due to the devotion the people of Barquisimeto have towards it as gratitude towards saving the city from a cholera outbreak that occurred in the city in the 19th century.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] In 2013, 3,000,000 faithful honored the Divina Pastora.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is built on the terrace of the same name, on the banks of the Turbio River, about 600 meters (~2000 feet) above sea level, gradually sloping from 520 metres (1,710 feet) in the eastern part of the city to 700 metres (2,300 feet) in the west.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] To the northwest of Barquisimeto there are the Saroche hills (e.g.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Cerro Copeyal at 1323 meters a.s.l.) and to the northeast there are the Sierra de Aroa mountains (e.g.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Cerro Atravesado at 1712 meters a.s.l.).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is located in central-western Venezuela, 363 km (226 mi) from Caracas, the country's capital city.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Being a point of convergence of major road and rail routes, it has a diverse economy and has grown into a large city of 930,000 inhabitants.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Its flat relief has enabled a systematic urban grid with streets numbered in ascending numerical order, and consistent signage that helps with locating addresses.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto has an average temperature of 25 °C (77 °F) throughout the year; its driest period is from December to March.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] In the city, a hot semi-arid climate (Köppen *BSh*) is dominant.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Located in that region, Barquisimeto records 550 millimetres or 21.7 inches of rain per year and its average temperature ranges 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] However, in higher regions near the Andes, temperatures are lower and the rain is more constant.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] For instance, in Sanare city, the annual average rainfall is 835 millimetres or 32.9 inches.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is a city with a historic vocation by academic knowledge, and boasts a considerable sample of universities and institutes of higher education in Venezuela, has a high and growing student population from all over the country.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Major universities in the city include Universidad Centroccidental Lisandro Alvarado and Universidad Nacional Experimental Politécnica Antonio José de Sucre.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The Transbarca system is a new "bus rapid transit" (BRT) system under construction, which was originally planned to use trolleybuses.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] When construction began, in 2006, the system was projected to serve an average of 170,000 people per day when completed, using 80 trolleybuses operating along 30 km (19 mi) of exclusive lanes, across the metropolitan area.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Service was planned to include an express route of 22 km (14 mi) along with one local route of 8 km (5 mi).
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] With 52 stations, the BRT system is to include a centralized system of communication and security, and structures for easy access for elderly and disabled people.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] It is to be complemented with feeder routes, covering the areas of Greater Barquisimeto the BRT line will not serve, which will connect with the main line at terminal stations.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Although 80 articulated trolleybuses were purchased from Neoplan and delivered around 2008–09, the plans to operate the Transbarca system with those vehicles were dropped in 2013.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] In addition to reasons of cost, an inadequate supply of electricity with which to power the system was cited in the announcement of the decision.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The city has an airport called Jacinto Lara International Airport.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] The city is home to several notable baseball and football teams.
[src:2024-baseball5-world-cup/barquisimeto] Several other sports also have Barquisimeto as their home.
